Review: Walks that line of a cliche sports drama, pulling from its tradition and subverting it enough to make something even more powerful. The performances easily took it over the top, grounding each scene in some rugged, stoic face just on the edge of tears. I’m here for the brothers.

The tabloid-ism of this film is not only at the center of its plot, but its entire construction. It is a testament to the unreal and our own infatuation with an endless stream of frivolous stories. No matter how humane we might see ourselves, those juicy details will always outweigh any interest in the truth. May December holds a mirror to such a nasty, universal habit - caking even the most sobering of stories with dramatic one-liners and orchestral hits.…
What are you trying to tell us Obama?
Great concept but ultimately felt unsure of itself and couldn’t really hold interest.
Just relax and enjoy the scenery.

Movie: The Hunger Games: The Ballad of Songbirds & Snakes
Review: No one vetoed the three extra broadway songs here?

While I rarely hold anything against a longer runtime, this one certainly felt tedious. Mainly because there was little progression of its plot or characters. We understood the identities and actions of the three leads in the first ten minutes and not much changed to keep me intrigued. The story didn't evolve enough to warrant the time spent.

I liked a lot about this, especially the patience and stillness in which it used to tell a story that could have easily gone too far in the opposite direction. However I do think this same element that created so much claustrophobia and discomfort also led bits to feel pretty tedious and too muted to really keep me in.
I will think about this for a long time.
I felt things I have never felt before...
Making aimlessness look so aesthetically pleasing.
